data.content:
Then register it in `Program.cs`:

```csharp
// Program.cs

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Add Problem Details services
builder.Services.AddProblemDetails();

// Register the global exception handler
builder.Services.AddExceptionHandler<GlobalExceptionHandler>();

var app = builder.Build();

// Use the exception handler middleware (must be early in the pipeline)
app.UseExceptionHandler();

// Your endpoints - no try-catch needed
app.MapGet("/items/{id}", (int id) =>
{
    if (id < 0) throw new ArgumentException("ID must be positive");
    if (id == 0) throw new KeyNotFoundException("Item not found");
    return Results.Ok(new { Id = id, Name = "Example" });
});

app.Run();
```

**How it works:**

1. `AddExceptionHandler<T>()` registers your handler with DI
2. `UseExceptionHandler()` catches any unhandled exception in the pipeline
3. Your `IExceptionHandler` maps exceptions → status codes and writes a `ProblemDetails` JSON response
4. 500 errors suppress `Detail` to avoid leaking internals

**Sample 404 response:**
```json
{
  "status": 404,
  "title": "Resource not found",
  "detail": "Item not found"
}
```

This requires .NET 8+. The `IExceptionHandler` interface was introduced in .NET 8 as the recommended replacement for the older `UseExceptionHandler(Action)` pattern.
